# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gnome-libadwaita
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] In computing, a **desktop environment** (**DE**) is an implementation of the desktop metaphor made of a bundle of programs running on top of a computer operating system that share a common graphical user interface (GUI), sometimes described as a graphical shell.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] The desktop environment was seen mostly on personal computers until the rise of mobile computing.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Desktop GUIs help the user to easily access and edit files, while they usually do not provide access to all of the features found in the underlying operating system.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Instead, the traditional command-line interface (CLI) is still used when full control over the operating system is required.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] A desktop environment typically consists of icons, windows, toolbars, folders, wallpapers and desktop widgets (see Elements of graphical user interfaces and WIMP).
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] A GUI might also provide drag and drop functionality and other features that make the desktop metaphor more complete.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] A desktop environment aims to be an intuitive way for the user to interact with the computer using concepts which are similar to those used when interacting with the physical world, such as buttons and windows.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] While the term *desktop environment* originally described a style of user interfaces following the desktop metaphor, it has also come to describe the programs that realize the metaphor itself.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] This usage has been popularized by projects such as the Common Desktop Environment, KDE, and GNOME.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] On a system that offers a desktop environment, a window manager in conjunction with applications written using a widget toolkit are generally responsible for most of what the user sees.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] The window manager supports the user interactions with the environment, while the toolkit provides developers a software library for applications with a unified look and behavior.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] A windowing system of some sort generally interfaces directly with the underlying operating system and libraries.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] This provides support for graphical hardware, pointing devices, and keyboards.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] The window manager generally runs on top of this windowing system.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] While the windowing system may provide some window management functionality, this functionality is still considered to be part of the window manager, which simply happens to have been provided by the windowing system.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Applications that are created with a particular window manager in mind usually make use of a windowing toolkit, generally provided with the operating system or window manager.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] A windowing toolkit gives applications access to widgets that allow the user to interact graphically with the application in a consistent way.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] The first desktop environment was created by Xerox and was sold with the Xerox Alto in the 1970s.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] The Alto was generally considered by Xerox to be a personal office computer; it failed in the marketplace because of poor marketing and a very high price tag.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] With the Lisa, Apple introduced a desktop environment on an affordable personal computer, which also failed in the market.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] The desktop metaphor was popularized on commercial personal computers by the original Macintosh from Apple in 1984, and was popularized further by Windows from Microsoft since the 1990s.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] As of 2014, the most popular desktop environments are descendants of these earlier environments, including the Windows shell used in Microsoft Windows, and the Aqua environment used in macOS.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Microsoft Windows dominates in marketshare among personal computers with a desktop environment.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Computers using Unix-like operating systems such as macOS, ChromeOS, Linux, BSD or Solaris are much less common; however, as of 2015 there is a growing market for low-cost Linux PCs using the X Window System or Wayland with a broad choice of desktop environments.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Among the more popular of these are Google's Chromebooks and Chromeboxes, Intel's NUC, the Raspberry Pi, etc.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] On tablets and smartphones, the situation is the opposite, with Unix-like operating systems dominating the market, including iOS (BSD-derived), Android, Tizen, Sailfish and Ubuntu (all Linux-derived).
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Microsoft's Windows phone, Windows RT and Windows 10 are used on a much smaller number of tablets and smartphones.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] However, the majority of Unix-like operating systems dominant on handheld devices do not use the X11 desktop environments used by other Unix-like operating systems, relying instead on interfaces based on other technologies.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] On systems running the X Window System (typically Unix-family systems such as Linux, the BSDs, and formal UNIX distributions), desktop environments are much more dynamic and customizable to meet user needs.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] In this context, a desktop environment typically consists of several separate components, including a window manager (such as Mutter or KWin), a file manager (such as Files or Dolphin), a set of graphical themes, together with toolkits (such as GTK+ and Qt) and libraries for managing the desktop.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] All these individual modules can be exchanged and independently configured to suit users, but most desktop environments provide a default configuration that works with minimal user setup.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Some window managers‍—‌such as IceWM, Fluxbox, Openbox, ROX Desktop and Window Maker‍—‌contain relatively sparse desktop environment elements, such as an integrated spatial file manager, while others like evilwm and wmii do not provide such elements.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Not all of the program code that is part of a desktop environment has effects which are directly visible to the user.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] KDE, for example, provides so-called KIO slaves which give the user access to a wide range of virtual devices.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] These I/O slaves are not available outside the KDE environment.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] In 1996 the KDE was announced, followed in 1997 by the announcement of GNOME.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Xfce is a smaller project that was also founded in 1996, and focuses on speed and modularity, just like LXDE which was started in 2006.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] A comparison of X Window System desktop environments demonstrates the differences between environments.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] GNOME and KDE were usually seen as dominant solutions, and these are still often installed by default on Linux systems.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] In the early 2000s, KDE reached maturity.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] The Appeal and ToPaZ projects focused on bringing new advances to the next major releases of both KDE and GNOME respectively.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Although striving for broadly similar goals, GNOME and KDE do differ in their approach to user ergonomics.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] KDE encourages applications to integrate and interoperate, is highly customizable, and contains many complex features, all whilst trying to establish sensible defaults.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] GNOME on the other hand is more prescriptive, and focuses on the finer details of essential tasks and overall simplification.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Accordingly, each one attracts a different user and developer community.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Technically, there are numerous technologies common to all Unix-like desktop environments, most obviously the X Window System.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Accordingly, the freedesktop.org project was established as an informal collaboration zone with the goal being to reduce duplication of effort.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] As GNOME and KDE focus on high-performance computers, users of less powerful or older computers often prefer alternative desktop environments specifically created for low-performance systems.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Most commonly used lightweight desktop environments include LXDE and Xfce; they both use GTK+, which is the same underlying toolkit GNOME uses.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] The MATE desktop environment, a fork of GNOME 2, is comparable to Xfce in its use of RAM and processor cycles, but is often considered more as an alternative to other lightweight desktop environments.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] For a while, GNOME and KDE enjoyed the status of the most popular Linux desktop environments; later, other desktop environments grew in popularity.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] In April 2011, GNOME introduced a new interface concept with its version 3, while a popular Linux distribution Ubuntu introduced its own new desktop environment, Unity.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Some users preferred to keep the traditional interface concept of GNOME 2, resulting in the creation of MATE as a GNOME 2 fork.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] The most common desktop environment on personal computers is Windows Shell in Microsoft Windows.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Microsoft has made significant efforts in making Windows shell visually pleasing.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] As a result, Microsoft has introduced theme support in Windows 98, the various Windows XP visual styles, the Aero brand in Windows Vista, the Microsoft design language (codenamed "Metro") in Windows 8, and the Fluent Design System and Windows Spotlight in Windows 10.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Windows shell can be extended via Shell extensions.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Many mainstream desktop environments for Unix-like operating systems, including KDE, GNOME, Xfce, and LXDE, use the X Window System or Wayland, any of which may be selected by users, and are not tied exclusively to the operating system in use.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] The desktop environment for macOS, which is also a Unix-like system, is Aqua, which uses the Quartz graphics layer, rather than using X or Wayland.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] A number of other desktop environments also exist, including (but not limited to) CDE, EDE, GEM, IRIX Interactive Desktop, Sun's Java Desktop System, Jesktop, Mezzo, Project Looking Glass, ROX Desktop, UDE, Xito, XFast.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Moreover, there exists FVWM-Crystal, which consists of a powerful configuration for the FVWM window manager, a theme and further adds, altogether forming a "construction kit" for building up a desktop environment.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] X window managers that are meant to be usable stand-alone — without another desktop environment — also include elements reminiscent of those found in typical desktop environments, most prominently Enlightenment.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Other examples include OpenBox, Fluxbox, WindowLab, Fvwm, as well as Window Maker and AfterStep, which both feature the NeXTSTEP GUI look and feel.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] The Amiga approach to desktop environment was noteworthy: the original Workbench desktop environment in AmigaOS evolved through time to originate an entire family of descendants and alternative desktop solutions.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Some of those descendants are the Scalos, the Ambient desktop of MorphOS, and the Wanderer desktop of the AROS open source OS.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] WindowLab also contains features reminiscent of the Amiga UI.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Third-party Directory Opus software, which was originally just a navigational file manager program, evolved to become a complete Amiga desktop replacement called Directory Opus Magellan.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] OS/2 (and derivatives such as eComStation and ArcaOS) use the Workplace Shell.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Earlier versions of OS/2 used the Presentation Manager.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] The BumpTop project was an experimental desktop environment.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/desktop-environment] Its main objective is to replace the 2D paradigm with a "real-world" 3D implementation, where documents can be freely manipulated across a virtual table.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/getting-started] This is the Flatpak manifest for your application.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/getting-started] You can use the manifest to define your project’s dependencies.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/getting-started] The default manifest depends on the latest stable version of the GNOME platform.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/getting-started] You can also include additional dependencies not provided by the GNOME runtime.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/getting-started] This is the main Meson build file, which defines how and what to build in your application.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/getting-started] This is the directory with the sources of your application, as well as the UI definition files for its widgets.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/getting-started] The GResource manifest for assets that will be built into the project using `glib-compile-resources`.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/getting-started] The list of files containing translatable, user-visible strings.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/getting-started] The schema file for the settings of the application.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/getting-started] The desktop entry file for the application.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/getting-started] The application metadata used by app stores and application distributors.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/getting-started] If you want to, you can now build and run the application by pressing the *Run Project* button, or Shift + Ctrl + Space.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/getting-started] The code in this tutorial is available on GitLab.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME is developed by the GNOME Project, which is composed of both volunteers and paid contributors, the largest corporate contributor being Red Hat.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] It is an international project that aims to develop frameworks for software development, to program end-user applications based on these frameworks, and to coordinate efforts for the internationalization, localization, and accessibility of that software.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] In 2023 and 2024, GNOME received €1,000,000 from Germany's Sovereign Tech Fund.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Since GNOME 2, productivity has been a key focus for GNOME.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] To meet this end, the GNOME Human Interface Guidelines (HIG) were created.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] All GNOME programs share a coherent style of interfaces but are not limited to the employment of the same GUI widgets.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Rather, the design of the GNOME's interface is guided by concepts described in the HIG, itself relying on insights from cognitive ergonomics.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Following the HIG, developers can create high-quality, consistent, and usable GUI programs, as it addresses everything from interface design to the recommended pixel-based layout of widgets.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] However, critics have complained about GNOME ignoring traditional user interface conventions, and the wasting of screen real estate.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] During the GNOME 2 rewrite, many settings deemed of little value to the majority of users were removed.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME aims to make and keep the desktop environment physically and cognitively ergonomic for people with disabilities.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The GNOME Human Interface Guidelines try to take this into account as far as possible but specific issues are solved by special software.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME addresses computer accessibility issues by using the Accessibility Toolkit (ATK) application programming interface, which allows enhancing user experience by using special input methods and speech synthesis and speech recognition software.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Particular utilities are registered with ATK using Assistive Technology Service Provider Interface (AT-SPI), and become globally used throughout the desktop.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Several assistive technology providers, including Orca screen reader and Dasher input method, were developed specifically for use with GNOME.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The internationalization and localization of GNOME software relies on locale, and supports 197 languages with varying levels of completion, with some not being translated at all.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME Shell is the main graphical shell of GNOME.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] It features a top bar holding (from left to right) an Overview button, a clock and an integrated system status menu.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The application menu displays the name of the application in focus and provides access to functions such as accessing the application's preferences, closing the application, or creating a new application window.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The status menu holds various system status indicators, shortcuts to system settings, and session actions including logging out, switching users, locking the screen, and suspending the computer.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Clicking on the Activities button, moving the mouse to the top-left hot corner or pressing the Super key brings up the Overview.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The Overview gives users an overview of current activities and provides a way to switch between windows and workspaces and to launch applications.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The Dash on the bottom houses shortcuts to favorite applications, currently open windows, and an application picker button to show a list of all installed applications.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] A search bar appears at the top and a workspace list for viewing and switching between workspaces is directly above it.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Notifications appear from the top of the shell.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME Classic also adds the minimize and maximize buttons to window headers.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] There are a large number of GTK-based programs written by various authors.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Since the release of GNOME 3.0, GNOME Project concentrates on developing a set of programs that accounts for the GNOME Core Applications.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The commonalities of the GNOME Core Applications are the adherence to the current GNOME Human Interface Guidelines (HIG) as well as the tight integration with underlying GNOME layers like e.g.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GVfs (GNOME virtual filesystem) and also with one another e.g.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GOA (gnome-online-accounts) settings and GNOME Files with Google Drive and GNOME Photos with Google Photos.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Some programs are simply existing programs with a new name and revamped user interface, while others have been written from scratch.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The GNOME project provides a suite of software development tools to facilitate the creation of GNOME software.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] These tools are designed to streamline the development process for the GNOME ecosystem.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] These tools collectively provide a comprehensive development environment for creating software that aligns with the GNOME desktop and its design principles.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME Circle is a collection of applications which have been built to extend the GNOME platform, utilize GNOME technologies, and follow the GNOME human interface guidelines.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME was started on 15 August 1997 by Miguel de Icaza and Federico Mena as a free software project to develop a desktop environment and applications for it.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] It was founded in part because the K Desktop Environment, which was growing in popularity, relied on the Qt widget toolkit which used a proprietary software license until version 2.0 (June 1999).
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] In place of Qt, GTK (formerly called GIMP Toolkit) was chosen as the base of GNOME.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GTK is licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL), a free software license that allows software linking to it to use a much wider set of licenses, including proprietary software licenses.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME itself is licensed under the LGPL for its libraries and the GNU General Public License (GPL) for its applications.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME was formerly a part of the GNU Project, but that is no longer the case.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] In 2021, GNOME Executive Director Neil McGovern publicly tweeted that GNOME was not a GNU project and that he had been asking GNU to remove GNOME from their list of packages since 2019.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] In 2021, GNOME was removed from the list.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME proceeded to remove mentions of any link to GNU from their code and documentation.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The name "GNOME" was initially an acronym for *GNU Network Object Model Environment*, referring to the original intention of creating a distributed object framework similar to Microsoft's OLE, but the acronym was eventually dropped because it no longer reflected the vision of the GNOME project.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The California startup Eazel developed the Nautilus file manager from 1999 to 2001.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] De Icaza and Nat Friedman founded Helix Code (later Ximian) in 1999 in Massachusetts; this company developed GNOME's infrastructure and applications and was purchased by Novell in 2003.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] During the transition to GNOME 2 and shortly thereafter, there were brief talks about creating a *GNOME Office* suite.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] On 15 September 2003 GNOME-Office 1.0, consisting of AbiWord 2.0, GNOME-DB 1.0, and Gnumeric 1.2.0, was released.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Although some release planning for GNOME Office 1.2 was happening on the gnome-office mailing list, and Gnumeric 1.4 was announced as a part of it, the 1.2 release of the suite itself never materialized.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] As of 4 May 2014, the GNOME wiki only mentions "GNOME/GTK applications that are useful in an office environment".
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 2 was released in June 2002 and was very similar to a conventional desktop interface, featuring a simple desktop in which users could interact with virtual objects such as windows, icons, and files.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 2 started out with Sawfish as its default window manager, but later switched to Metacity in GNOME 2.2.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The handling of windows, applications, and files in GNOME 2 is similar to that of contemporary desktop operating systems.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] However, these features can be moved to almost any position or orientation the user desires, replaced with other functions, or removed altogether.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] As of 2009, GNOME 2 was the default desktop for OpenSolaris.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] In 2008, an increasing discontent among the community and developers about the lack of project direction and technical progress prompted the announcement of GNOME 3.0.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Originally, the plan was to make only incremental changes and avoid disruption for users.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] This changed when efforts led to the creation of the GNOME Shell.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 3 brought many enhancements to core software.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Many GNOME Core Applications also went through redesigns to provide a better user experience.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Mutter replaced Metacity as the default window manager, and Adwaita replaced Clearlooks as the default theme.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The release of GNOME 3 caused considerable controversy in the GNU and Linux communities.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Aiming to provide an easy-to-use and uncluttered user experience has led to some criticized design decisions, like the removal of *minimize* and *maximize* buttons, the simplification of configuration options, and visual cues that could lead to confusion.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Among those critical of the early releases of GNOME 3 is Linus Torvalds, the creator of the Linux kernel.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Torvalds abandoned GNOME for a while after the release of GNOME 3.0, saying, "The developers have apparently decided that it's 'too complicated' to actually do real work on your desktop, and have decided to make it really annoying to do".
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Over time, critical reception has grown more positive.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] In 2013, Torvalds resumed using GNOME, noting that "they have extensions now that are still much too hard to find; but with extensions you can make your desktop look almost as good as it used to look two years ago".
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Debian, a Linux distribution that had historically used GNOME 2, switched to Xfce when GNOME 3 was released, but re-adopted GNOME 3 in time for the release of Debian 8 "Jessie".
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Ubuntu switched from Unity to GNOME 3 with several extensions to resemble Unity, such as a persistent left application panel instead of a hidden dock and re-enabling desktop icons, with Ubuntu 17.10 Artful Aardvark in 2017.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] This release also saw the Ubuntu GNOME edition merge with the mainline release.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] However, Ubuntu Unity was then released, keeping the Unity desktop and continuing to update it.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] It immediately follows version 3, but adopts a new versioning scheme and a schedule of future major releases on a fixed six-month cycle (see Release Cycle).
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] With this quicker release cadence, major releases became somewhat leaner, because full rewrites of major packages were not occurring as often as they were in the jumps between GNOME 1.0, 2.0, and 3.0 versions.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 40 organizes the activities overview in a horizontal fashion, instead of using a vertical design like its predecessors.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The release also brings new touchpad gestures.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 42 was released on 23 March 2022 and introduced the option to screen record and switch light/dark themes using a new GTK API called Libadwaita.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Several default apps were replaced with more modern versions such as Text Editor instead of Gedit and Console instead of Terminal.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 43 (Guadalajara) was released on 21 September 2022 and introduced a new quick settings menu, a GNOME Files update to GTK4, and a new 'Device Security' panel in settings, among many other changes.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME Web was updated, bringing in support for web apps and experimental Firefox and Chrome extension support.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 44 (Kuala Lumpur) was released on 22 March 2023.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Named after Kuala Lumpur in recognition of work done by the GNOME.Asia community, GNOME 44 introduced a new file chooser grid view, updated settings panels, and redesigned accessibility settings.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The new quick settings menu introduced in GNOME 43 was updated, alongside the addition of several new apps and improvements to existing apps.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 45 (Rīga) was released on 20 September 2023.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] It introduced redesigned app styles alongside a new activities button, which replaced both the previous "Activities" label and the app menu with a graphical workspace indicator.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Other updates to the system bar included a new camera usage indicator and a keyboard shortcut to open and close the quick settings menu.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 45 also introduced two new image viewer and camera apps, keyboard backlight controls, and numerous enhancements to existing apps.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 46 (Kathmandu) was released on 20 March 2024 and featured an enhanced files app with global search, support for headless remote login via GDM, and a refreshed settings app, amongst many other app changes.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Other system changes included accessibility improvements and experimental support for variable refresh rates.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 47 (Denver) was released on 18 September 2024 and introduced support for user-selected accent colors in Libadwaita applications, allowing greater interface customization.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] It also brought improvements for low-resolution displays through automatic icon scaling, optimizations in screen recording with GPU hardware encoding, and various enhancements to performance, file navigation, and online accounts.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 48 (Bengaluru) was released on 19 March 2025 and is included in Fedora 42 and Ubuntu 25.04.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] This version introduced notification grouping by application (notification stacking), significant performance improvements such as dynamic triple buffering for smoother animations, and optimizations in CPU and memory usage across key system components.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] It also included improvements in file indexing and graphical stability on systems with dedicated GPUs.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 49 (Brescia) was released in September 2025 and is included in Fedora 43 and Ubuntu 25.10.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] It deprecated X11 support, disabling it by default.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] It also replaced the video player Totem and the document viewer Evince with Showtime and Papers, respectively, and introduced shutting down and restarting the computer when logged out.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 50 (Tokyo) was released on 18 March 2026.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 50 removed X11 support from the source code.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] It introduced new parental control features, accessibility improvements such as global options and reduced animations, and optimizations in core applications such as Files (Nautilus) and Calendar.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] It also added improvements to remote desktop with hardware acceleration, expanded graphics support (including enhancements for NVIDIA and variable refresh rates), and new options in system settings.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] By default, GNOME Flashback contains two panels (one on the top, and one to its opposite on the bottom) spanning the width of the screen.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The top panel usually contains navigation menus labeled "Applications" and "Places" in that order, as the "System" menu from GNOME 2.x has been replaced by a control panel in GNOME 3.x.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] These menus hold links to common applications and areas of the file system, respectively.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] A user menu placed on the opposite side of the screen, which has been available since GNOME 2.14 but has become more prominent in GNOME 3.x, holds access to account and system settings as well as options to log out, switch user, and shut down the computer.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The top panel usually contains a clock/calendar and a notification area, which can double as a sort of dock, as well.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The bottom panel is commonly empty by default (other than a set of buttons to navigate between desktops) due to its use in the navigation between windows (windows minimize to the bottom panel by default).
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Users can populate these panels with other completely customizable menus and buttons, including new menus, search boxes, and icons, with the icons in particular (called *launchers*) performing functions similar to the *quick-launch* feature found in the Microsoft Windows 98–Vista taskbar.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Other applications can also be attached to the panels, and the panels are highly reconfigurable: anything on these panels can be moved, removed, or configured in other ways.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The version of GNOME Panel available in the repository for Ubuntu 12.04 offers a modified version of Fallback Mode with the addition of a custom theme and ports of Ubuntu's own Indicators from their old GNOME 2.x desktop.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Trisquel uses Fallback Mode (Flashback) for its main desktop, because GNOME Shell requires 3D acceleration as it relies on graphics composition, while some free software drivers do not support 3D acceleration, among other reasons like more usability and more stability.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Each of the component software products in the GNOME project has its own version number and release schedule.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] However, individual module maintainers coordinate their efforts to create a full GNOME stable release on an approximately six-month schedule, alongside its underlying libraries such as GTK and GLib.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Some experimental projects are excluded from these releases.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Before GNOME 40, GNOME version numbers followed the scheme *v.xx.yy*.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Here, *v* is a major version, which can include large changes such as ABI breakage; these have no regular schedule and occur in response to requirements for large-scale changes.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] *xx* is a minor version, released on the above schedule of approximately every 6 months, in which the 1- or 2-digit number's parity indicates the type of release: if *xx* is even (e.g.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] 3.20) the release is considered stable, whereas if *xx* is odd, it represents a current development snapshot (e.g.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] 3.21) that will eventually evolve into the next stable release.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] 3.20.6; these are made on a frequency of weeks in order to fix issues, add non-breaking enhancements, etc.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME 40 started a new versioning scheme in which a single number is incremented with each semi-annual release.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The number is followed by a dot and then "alpha", "beta", or "rc" for a development release, or a decimal for a minor stable release (much like the *yy* mentioned previously).
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME releases are made to the main FTP server in the form of source code with configure scripts, which are compiled by operating system vendors and integrated with the rest of their systems before distribution.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Most vendors only use stable and tested versions of GNOME and provide it in the form of easily installed, pre-compiled packages.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The source code of every stable and development version of GNOME is stored in the GNOME git source code repository.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] A number of build scripts (such as JHBuild or formerly GARNOME) are available to help automate the process of compiling the source code.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Since the introduction of Discourse forum in 2019, the discussion moved from mailing lists and in October 2022, the project announced the plan to close all its public mailing lists.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME developers and users gather at an annual GUADEC meeting to discuss the current state and the future direction of GNOME.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME incorporates standards and programs from freedesktop.org to better support interoperability with other desktops.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] GNOME is mainly written in C, XML, C++, C#, HTML, Vala, Python, JavaScript, CSS, and more.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] A number of language bindings are available.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The GLib data structures and utilities library, GObject object and type system and GTK widget toolkit along with the Adwaita design language implemented by libadwaita, comprise the central part of the GNOME development platform.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] The GNOME desktop environment does not consist solely of the graphical control element library GTK and the core applications that make use of it.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] There are quite a few additional software packages that make up the GNOME desktop environment, such as the above.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Wayland support was introduced in GNOME 3.10 and deemed "for the majority of users […] a usable day to day experience" by 3.20, at which point Wayland became the default user session.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] With GNOME 3.24, Wayland compatibility was extended to Nvidia drivers.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] In GNOME 3.30 or later, it was possible to run GNOME without X11 running at startup, using only Wayland.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] In GNOME 50, using the X11 session in Mutter is no longer possible, and GNOME became one of the first desktop environments to only support Wayland.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] X11 applications can still be run though XWayland.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] In May 2011 Lennart Poettering proposed systemd as a GNOME dependency.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] As systemd is available only on Linux, the proposal led to a discussion of possibly dropping support for other platforms in future GNOME releases.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Since GNOME 3.2, multiseat support has only been available on systems using systemd.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] In November 2012 the GNOME release team concluded there will be no compile time dependency on systemd for basic functionality, like session tracking.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] For non-basic functionality, like power management, compile time dependency is possible.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] For example, there is no concept of systemd inhibitors in alternatives like consolekit.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] A package manager may want to ensure that the system is not turned off while the upgrade is taking place.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Since GNOME 49 systemd became a stronger dependency.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p01] Adrian Vovk had announced two major changes: GDM is gaining a dependency on systemd’s userdb infrastructure and the builtin service manager of gnome-session is being removed.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p02] GNOME OS is an operating system designed to provide a streamlined, container-centric platform that serves as both an experimental testbed and a showcase for GNOME's user interface and application ecosystem.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p02] Unlike many Linux distributions, GNOME OS is not based on other distributions such as Arch Linux, Debian, or Fedora Linux.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p02] It is built from the ground up using tools like BuildStream, Freedesktop SDK, and GNOME Build Meta, ensuring a clean and consistent environment tailored for GNOME development.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p02] This approach allows GNOME OS to provide a standardized platform for developers to develop the latest GNOME software without the variability introduced by other distributions.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p02] While GNOME OS shares similarities with immutable distributions like Fedora Silverblue, it remains distinct in its purpose and design, focusing solely on the GNOME ecosystem.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p02] The concept of GNOME OS began to take shape around 2010, with discussions and planning sessions focused on creating a more unified and cohesive system for GNOME.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p02] The vision was inspired by other platforms like Android, WebOS, and MeeGo, with the goal of designing an operating system that could offer a better experience for both users and developers.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p02] In 2012, during the GUADEC conference held in A Coruña, a significant planning session, known as a Birds of a Feather (BoF) session, was conducted on July 30.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p02] This session brought together key members of the GNOME community to discuss and plan the future direction of GNOME OS.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p02] The discussions covered several critical areas, including application development, testing, core user experience (UX), pattern language, and support for touch and mobile devices.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p02] Early OSTree-based build efforts were sometimes informally referred to as "**gnome-ostree**", but the continuous integration pipeline that emerged became known as **GNOME Continuous**, reflecting its primary role as a continuous integration and testing platform for GNOME.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p02] It was designed to provide a rolling-release environment where developers could test GNOME 3.x features and applications in isolation.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p02] Technologically, GNOME Continuous adopted OSTree for atomic updates, allowing the system to roll back to previous states if updates failed, ensuring system stability.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p02] This technology was later popularized by Fedora Silverblue and other immutable Linux distributions.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-p02] GNOME OS first became publicly visible as a testable reference platform around 2020, when the project published a “GNOME OS Nightly” page offering downloadable images and instructions for running the system in virtual machines or on real hardware.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] GNOME Shell is written in C and JavaScript as a plugin for Mutter.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] The first concepts for GNOME Shell were created during GNOME's *User Experience Hackfest* 2008 in Boston.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] After criticism of the traditional GNOME desktop and accusations of stagnation and lacking vision, the resulting discussion led to the announcement of *GNOME 3.0* in April 2009.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] Since then Red Hat has been the main driver of GNOME Shell's development.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] Pre-release versions of GNOME Shell were first made available in August 2009 and became regular, non-default part of GNOME in version 2.28 in September 2009.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] It was finally shipped as GNOME's default user interface on April 6, 2011.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] As graphical shell (graphical front-end/graphical shell/UX/UI) of the GNOME desktop environment, its design is guided by the GNOME UX Design Team.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] GNOME Shell is tightly integrated with Mutter, a compositing window manager and Wayland compositor.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] It is based upon Clutter to provide visual effects and hardware acceleration.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] According to GNOME Shell maintainer Owen Taylor, it is set up as a Mutter plugin largely written in JavaScript and uses GUI widgets provided by GTK+ version 3.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] The functionality of GNOME Shell can be changed with extensions, which can be written in JavaScript.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] Users can find and install extensions using the GNOME extensions website.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] Some of these extensions are hosted in GNOME's git repository, though they are not official.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] GNOME Shell has received mixed reviews: it has been criticized for a variety of reasons, mostly related to design decisions and reduced user control over the environment.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] For example, users in the free software community have raised concerns that the planned tight integration with Mutter will mean that users of GNOME Shell will not be able to switch to an alternative window manager without breaking their desktop.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] In particular, users might not be able to use Compiz with GNOME Shell while retaining access to the same types of features that older versions of GNOME allowed.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gnome-shell] Reviews have generally become more positive over time, with upcoming releases addressing many of the annoyances reported by users.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] The GTK team releases new versions on a regular basis.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GTK 4 and GTK 3 are actively maintained, while GTK 2 is no longer supported.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GTK 1 is independently maintained by the CinePaint project.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] The GTK library contains a set of graphical control elements (widgets); version 3.22.16 contains 186 active and 36 deprecated widgets.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GTK is an object-oriented widget toolkit written in the programming language C; it uses GObject (that is, the GLib object system) for object orientation.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] While GTK is mainly used with windowing systems based on Wayland (and prior to that on Wayland's predecessor X11), it works on other platforms, including Microsoft Windows (interfaced with the Windows API), and macOS (interfaced with Quartz).
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] There is also an HTML5 back-end named *Broadway*, although this was deprecated in 2025 with the X11 backend to indicate both would be removed in GTK version 5.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GTK uses Vulkan or GL to draw most graphical elements.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GTK can be configured to change the look of the widgets drawn with its CSS engine.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] CSS can be used both at the system/user level, for all applications, and set by the application.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GDK acts as a wrapper around the low-level functions provided by the underlying windowing and graphics systems.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GSK is the rendering and scene graph API for GTK.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GSK lies between the graphical control elements (widgets) and the rendering.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GSK was finally merged into GTK version 3.90 released March 2017.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GtkBuilder allows user interfaces to be designed without writing code.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] The interface is described in an Extensible Markup Language (XML) file which is written by hand or generated by a GUI designer, which is then loaded at runtime and the objects created automatically.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] The description of the user interface is independent from the programming language being used.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] Language bindings are available for using GTK from languages other than C, including C++, Genie, JavaScript, Perl, Python, Vala, and others.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GTK supports various backends, which provides different ways to display GTK applications depending on the system and environment.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] There are several GUI designers for GTK.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] The GTK Inspector is a built-in interactive debugging tool in GTK, allowing developers to inspect and modify UI elements, test CSS changes, and analyze widget structure in real time.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] It can be enabled using the `Control + Shift + I` or `Control + Shift + D` shortcuts, or by setting the `GTK_DEBUG=interactive` environment variable.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] It was introduced with GTK version 3.14.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GTK is mainly developed by The GNOME Project, which also develops the GNOME Development Platform and the GNOME Desktop Environment.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GNOME developers and users gather at an annual *GNOME Users And Developers European Conference* GUADEC meeting to discuss GNOME's current state and future direction.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GNOME incorporates standards and programs from freedesktop.org to better interoperate with other desktops.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] Many GNOME applications have been ported to GTK 4, which was released in December 2020, however some still use GTK+ 3 (GIMP being a major one).
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] The master branch of GTK utilizes Meson for its build automation.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GTK (and GNOME, GLib, etc.) formerly utilized the GNU Build System (named Autotools) as the build automation system of choice.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] Since August 14, 2017, the Autotools build system files have been dropped.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] The most common criticism of GTK is the lack of backward-compatibility in major updates, most notably in the application programming interface (API) and theming.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] As a result, application and theme developers often have to rewrite parts of their code to ensure compatibility with newer version of GTK.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] The compatibility breaks between minor releases during the GTK 3.x development cycle was explained in 2013 by Benjamin Otte as due to strong pressures to innovate, such as providing the features modern users expect and supporting the increasingly influential Wayland display server protocol.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] With the release of GTK 4, the pressure from the need to innovate will have been released and the balance between stability and innovation will tip toward stability.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] Similarly, recent changes to theming are specifically intended to improve and stabilise that part of the API, meaning some investment now should be rewarded later.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] However, in 2025, GTK 5 is described in the official documentation as "a major new version of GTK that breaks both API and ABI compared to GTK 4.x.", like GTK 3 and 4.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GTK programs can be run on desktop environments based on X11 and Wayland, or others including ones not made with GTK, provided the needed libraries are installed; this includes macOS if X11.app is installed.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GTK can be also run on Microsoft Windows.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] It is used by some popular cross-platform applications like Pidgin and GIMP. wxWidgets, a cross-platform GUI toolkit, uses GTK on Linux by default.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] Other ports include DirectFB (for example used by the Debian installer).
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] Several desktop environments utilize GTK as the widget toolkit.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] For syntax highlighting there is GtkSourceView, "source code editing widget".
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GtkSourceView is maintained by GNOME separately from GTK as a library: gtksourceview.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GtkSpell is a library separate from GTK.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] Enchant is a wrapper for ispell, hunspell, etc., the actual spell checker engine/software.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GtkSpell uses GTK's GtkTextView widget, to highlight misspelled words and offer replacement.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] Finally GTK was re-written to be object-oriented and was renamed GTK+.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] This was first used in the 0.99 release of GIMP.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GTK was subsequently adopted for maintenance by the GNOME Foundation, which uses it in the GNOME desktop environment.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] The GTK 2.0.0 release (2002) series introduced new features which include improved text rendering using Pango, a new theme engine, improved accessibility using the Accessibility Toolkit, transition to Unicode using UTF-8 strings, and a more flexible API.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] Starting with version 2.8, released in 2005, GTK 2 depends on the Cairo graphics library for rendering vector graphics.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GTK version 3.0.0 (2011) included revised input device handling, support for themes written with CSS-like syntax, and the ability to receive information about other opened GTK applications.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] The '+' was dropped returning to simply 'GTK' in February 2019 during a Hackathon.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] Release of the first GTK 4 version was in December 2020.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] At the 2018 edition of DevConf.cz, Matthias Clasen gave an overview of the then-current state of GTK 4 development, including a high-level explanation of how rendering and input worked in GTK 3, what changes were being made to GTK 4, and the reasons for those changes.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] Examples of things that have become possible with GTK 4 were given as well.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] One of the main changes made during the GTK 4 development cycle (i.e.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/gtk-4] GTK 3.92, etc.) was the removal of user customization options (like individual keyboard shortcuts that could be set in GTK+ 2), and the delegation of functionality to ancillary objects instead of encoding it into the base classes provided by GTK.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/human-interface-guidelines] The central aim of a HIG is to create a consistent experience across the environment (generally an operating system or desktop environment), including the applications and other tools being used.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/human-interface-guidelines] This means both applying the same visual design and creating consistent access to and behaviour of common elements of the interface – from simple ones such as buttons and icons up to more complex constructions, such as dialog boxes.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/human-interface-guidelines] HIGs are recommendations and advice meant to help developers create better applications.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/human-interface-guidelines] Developers sometimes intentionally choose to break them if they think that the guidelines do not fit their application, or usability testing reveals an advantage in doing so.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/human-interface-guidelines] But in turn, the organization publishing the HIG might withhold endorsement of the application.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/human-interface-guidelines] Mozilla Firefox's user interface, for example, goes against the GNOME project's HIG, which is one of the project's main arguments for including GNOME Web instead of Firefox in the GNOME distribution.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/human-interface-guidelines] Human interface guidelines often describe the visual design rules, including icon and window design and style.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/human-interface-guidelines] Much less frequently, they specify how user input and interaction mechanisms work.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/human-interface-guidelines] Aside from the detailed rules, guidelines sometimes also make broader suggestions about how to organize and design the application and write user-interface text.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/human-interface-guidelines] In this case the HIG will build on a platform HIG by adding the common semantics for a range of application functions.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/human-interface-guidelines] In contrast to platform-specific guidelines, cross-platform guidelines aren't tied to a distinct platform.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/human-interface-guidelines] These guidelines make recommendations which should be true on any platform.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/human-interface-guidelines] Since this isn't always possible, cross-platform guidelines may weigh the compliance against the imposed work load.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Prior to version 3.0, the GNOME desktop environment utilized the Clearlooks theme.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] In October 2008, designers and developers met at the GNOME User Experience Hackfest in Boston.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] During this event, the concept of a GNOME Shell was conceived.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Some very early mockups were produced that entertained the possibility of differing design from the previous incarnation of GNOME.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Red Hat designers Jon McCann and Jeremy Perry authored a document, drawn from a broad consensus of collaborative effort, that aimed to set standards and direction for GNOME's design.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] In February 2010, GNOME designers met again, and produced several more publicly-available mockups.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Also produced from the 2010 meeting was the decision to use Cantarell as the default typeface.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Cantarell had been designed by Dave Crossland during his studies in the Department of Typography and Graphic Communication at the University of Reading the previous year.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] It was officially added to GNOME Shell in February 2011, and the GNOME Project agreed to maintain and extend the font as needed.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] On January 19, 2011, Carlos Garnacho announced his completion of a tangible GTK theme implementation of Adwaita that could then be utilized by GNOME.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] The first major Linux distribution to ship with GNOME 3.0 and Adwaita as a default was Fedora Linux when it released version 15 on May 24, 2011.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Due to GTK's strong ties with GNOME, Adwaita's theme had replaced "Raleigh" as the default GTK theme in 2014; however, in preparation for the release of libadwaita, the theme was removed from GTK in favor of a divergent, simpler one on January 14, 2021.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] This clear demarcation allowed for both GNOME, with its own design needs, and GTK, with its need for a simple theme that could be extended by downstream projects, to simultaneously prosper.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Libadwaita first shipped with the release of GNOME 42.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Adwaita is characterized by its clean, modern aesthetic and focus on usability.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Through the GNOME Human Interface Guidelines, Adwaita's design principles are rooted in simplicity, consistency, and accessibility.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] The libadwaita library was created to further develop Adwaita as a more closely-adherent component of the GNOME Human Interface Guidelines.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Libadwaita is a library augmenting the GTK widget toolkit in a manner conformant with the GNOME Human Interface Guidelines.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] It lets applications change their layout based on the available screen space, integrates the Adwaita stylesheet, allows runtime recoloring with named colors and adds APIs to support the cross-desktop dark style preference.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Libadwaita offers tools for creating applications with responsive design, allowing applications to adapt their layouts based on the available screen space, which aids in the development of smartphone-compatible GNOME applications.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Libhandy is a library sponsored by Purism, which was the predecessor of Libadwaita.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] The libhandy project was used as the basis for libadwaita.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] The GNOME Human Interface Guidelines (HIG) serve as a comprehensive guide to designing applications for the GNOME desktop environment.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] It helps with creation of user interfaces that align with GNOME's design philosophy, and is the basis for Adwaita's own style and design standards.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Adwaita's color palette is used in design of application icons and in illustrations.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] It consists of several color shade families that are not named beyond their number designations.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Those lacking saturation are known as "light" and "dark".
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] This naming convention extends into the applied concept of user interface styles, where users can choose a base style for on-screen widget components that creates a light or dark overall look and feel.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Beginning with GNOME 48, Adwaita adopted a new typeface family known as "Adwaita Fonts".
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] The Adwaita Fonts family is a slight modification of the Inter typeface family, however it also includes a monospaced font known as "Adwaita Mono", which is a modified version of Iosevka.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] With this change, the default typeface for GNOME will be known as "Adwaita Sans".
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Previously, Adwaita used the contemporary humanist sans-serif Cantarell typeface that was designed by Dave Crossland.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Corresponding with the 3.28 version release of GNOME in 2018, Cantarell was expanded to include light and extra bold weights.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Adwaita defines two separate style classes of icons that are meant to differentiate between concepts used for applications and user interfaces.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Whereas applications use full-color in their primary icons, "symbolic" icons, monochromatic by design, are meant for user interfaces.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Each app targeted for GNOME should have a primary icon.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] The GNOME Human Interface Guidelines prescribe that an app's icon should correspond to a simple, recognizable metaphor.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] They are not meant to be flat, but rather simplistic, and can contain some depth.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] App developers can request an icon from the GNOME Design Team in a GitLab repository.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] In user interfaces, even simpler, monochromatic icons that work well when viewed at small sizes are used.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] If color is needed, it is expected that they should be programmatically re-colored.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] The GNOME Shell was the primary vehicle for the original development of Adwaita's theme and icons.
[src:gnome-libadwaita/libadwaita] Similarly, Phosh, Purism's mobile shell, serves in the same role.
